          User's manual
        
        The command line format for BinShow is:
        
                BINSHOW [drive:][path]filename [[drive:][path]filename2]
        or      BINSHOW /REF
        or      BINSHOW /?
        
        where  [drive:][path]filename  is the file that is to be shown, and
        [drive:][path]filename2  is  the file to compare it to, if you want
        (you may display one or two files).
        
        /? shows the program's quick help screen.
        
        /REF loads in a reference table instead of a file.
        
        When  you  have  started the program and is inside the file viewer,
        you   will  see  two  status  lines,  the  file  contens  and  some
        information  on  the screen. The upper line contains the file name.
        If  you  press  the  spacebar  it  will change to headlines for the
        contens.  These  are:  Address  =  current address, Binary = binary
        contens  (base  2),  Oct.  = octal contens (base 8), Dec. = decimal
        contens  (base 10), Hex. = hexadecimal contens (base 16) and ASCII,
        which  shows  the  current ASCII character. In addition this column
        will contain the special ASCII name, if there is any (available for
        characters  0-32  and 127). When showing two files, both file names
        will be shown at the same time (without their path).
        
        You may scroll the listing up or down one line with the up and down
        arrows,  a  page  with  Page Up and Page Down, a kilobyte with ctrl
        plus  Page  Up  or Page Down or to the beginning or end of the file
        with  Home  or End. To switch the binary showing between ones/zeros
        and  stars/spaces  (to  show  pictures),  press Tab. The program is
        exited by pressing Escape.
        
        If  you  think  that  you  are  seeing to little of the file on the
        screen, you may, if you graphics card allows it, change into a mode
        with  more lines. On an EGA card there is a 50 line mode and on VGA
        60 lines. With ANSI.SYS loaded you can enter:
         MODE CON LINES=l COLS=c
        where  l is the number of lines and c the columns. Please note that
        the number of columns must be at least 80.
        
